title: For Sale:  WWI Pattern 14 Rifle - Drill Rifle, w/bayonet
postcontent: Need a cool wall hanger? Or a really long shish kebob for roasting a hole side of beef over the fire? This one's perfect.   Demilled British WWI P14 rifle, with an original bayonet and scabbard. This poor thing has a sad history. I found it welded to a gun shop sign (yes, welded). After cutting a deal with the owner, and many painstaking hours on a ladder with a dremel and hack saw, we got it down. Fortunately, before putting it up, the entire rifle had been shellacked, and after cleaning it up, it was in surprisingly good condition. With the help of my very skilled father, the only noticeable signs that it ever had been welded are a spot on the rear sight blade and on the barrel, where they used stainless steel flux to weld it to the bolts on the sign. But those spots are flush, and basically just bare metal spots, no material added. The bolt had been welded closed as well, but we were able to carefully cut that and fare it in with the normal contours of the rifle, so the bolt actually functions, and the hammer and firing pin fire, safety switch moves and works, everything. Follower and follower spring have been removed. The barrel was plugged with a rod through the chamber by the British military in order to make it a drill rifle (see the picture of the spot in the photos below), and all parts have been marked "DP" for "drill purposes". There are numerous stamps and markings on the receiver area (see pics). Rear ladder sights are intact and in good condition. The disc cutout where there would normally be a brass unit disc marking has been filled with a leather disc (this is how it was when I found it). Stock does still retain the mount for the rifle grenade sight on the left front side. Comes with an original British khaki web sling installed.   The bayonet is a functioning bayonet in good condition. There is some non-active pitting, but overall it's a very solid bayonet. Made by Remington in Nov of 1913, for the British, and stamped with the British crown and broad arrow. Comes with the correct British leather scabbard. Put it on the end of the rifle, and you've got a great spear. :-) Asking $320 plus shipping. I can ship, but it does require an FFL if you're out of state since the receiver is not cut. Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  S&W 629-4 Mountain Gun
postcontent:
Used Smith & Wesson 629-4 Mountain Gun in .44 Magnum (can also shoot .44 Special).  Fairly rare, these were "special run" guns with limited editions in a given year. As far as I can tell by research, there were two main runs of this gun & caliber combo, one in 1989 and one in 1994.  This gun, with a BSS serial prefix, is probably from the 1994 run (I've owned it since 2003).  This one appears to have been slightly customized, as Mountain Guns usually came with a plain black front sight, not the red ramp sight shown. The 629-4 is the last version to have the hammer-mounted firing pin, instead of the transfer bar system of later guns, and best of all, this is pre-Hillary Hole. 
Gun is in excellent condition for being old enough to drink.  Bore is crisp and bright, there are no major scratches, dents or dings besides two small (< 2mm) ones on the trigger guard (see picture).   Top strap is essentially untouched by flame cutting.  Cylinder does have a visible drag mark. 
This revolver comes with the attached custom wood grips, a set of Pachmayr Decelerator grips, a Galco Phoenix PHX126 dual-position (strong-side or cross-draw) holster and a soft case. 
 
Great pistol at a great price.
